1
00:01:35,160 --> 00:01:37,435
Here it is, gentlemen. The big problem.

2
00:01:37,520 --> 00:01:40,318
13-13 Experimental Battery.

3
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:43,949
I can tell you now,
we've had orders to solve it from the top seat.

4
00:01:44,040 --> 00:01:45,996
You mean WC?

5
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:48,389
WC. The top seat.

6
00:01:50,440 --> 00:01:52,476
As you know, we've tried everything.

7
00:01:52,560 --> 00:01:55,711
Brilliance, outstanding personality,
sheer naked courage.

8
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:57,631
The time has come to try something else.

9
00:01:57,720 --> 00:02:01,076
- Oh? And what's that, sir?
- Sheer bloody ignorance.

10
00:02:03,200 --> 00:02:05,475
How long are you going to be, then... sir?

11
00:02:05,560 --> 00:02:08,950
How long? When one is sent for
by one's brigadier

12
00:02:09,040 --> 00:02:13,670
to discuss a mission which is so hush-hush
that even oneself doesn't know what it is,

13
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:17,673
- one might be hours.
- Permission to pop down the NAAFI, sir.

14
00:02:17,760 --> 00:02:21,116
- I beg your pardon?
- Permission to pop down the NAAFI, sir.

15
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:24,556
Corporal, the enemy is poised
to strike across the Channel.

16
00:02:24,640 --> 00:02:28,679
The country is fighting for its life
and you want to pop down the NAAFI?

17
00:02:28,760 --> 00:02:32,036
- Well, in that case, I'll forget it.
- I'm very pleased to hear it.

18
00:02:32,120 --> 00:02:34,076
I beg your pardon... sir.

19
00:02:46,440 --> 00:02:48,510
Who are you, and what the devil are you doing?

20
00:02:48,600 --> 00:02:50,556
Captain Melly reporting, sir.

21
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:53,234
Brush yourself down!
Follow me to the conference room.

22
00:02:57,120 --> 00:02:59,429
(Horn honks)

23
00:02:59,520 --> 00:03:03,035
(Insistent honking)
- All right! All right! Why the bloody fanfare?

24
00:03:03,120 --> 00:03:05,350
Watch it, mate. New commanding officer.

25
00:03:05,440 --> 00:03:07,112
Blimey!

26
00:03:10,760 --> 00:03:13,399
Corporal... that man. He was wearing lipstick.

27
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:15,436
Lipstick, sir? Where?

28
00:03:15,520 --> 00:03:18,592
- On his face. Where do you think?
- It must be a burn or a scar, sir.

29
00:03:18,680 --> 00:03:21,274
- I hope you're right.
- So do I.

30
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:24,670
Frilly curtains? Baskets of flowers?

31
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:26,273
- <i>Brassieres?</i>
- <i>Pardon, sir?</i>

32
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:28,749
- Knickers!
- Same to you... sir.

33
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:47,230
(Belches)

34
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:55,716
- Captain Melly.
- No, you must have come to the wrong place.

35
00:03:55,800 --> 00:03:57,472
My name's Bull.

36
00:03:57,560 --> 00:03:59,596
No, no. <i>I'm</i> Melly. S Melly.

37
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,319
Pity. Have a drink.

38
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:04,277
Now, look here, Bull. I'm your relief.

39
00:04:04,360 --> 00:04:07,113
- <i>And there are certain things that...</i>
- My relief?

40
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:09,668
Oh, you little beauty!

41
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:13,280
I could kiss you!

42
00:04:13,360 --> 00:04:16,238
My re! Oooh, my relief!

43
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:19,312
I've got to go. My relief...

44
00:04:19,400 --> 00:04:21,960
He actually kissed me!

45
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,719
(Engine fires up)
- My case!

46
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:27,472
(Car accelerates)
- I say!

47
00:04:27,560 --> 00:04:29,278
<i>My case!</i>

48
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:34,638
(Belches)

49
00:04:36,680 --> 00:04:40,195
(Shouts)
Welcome to 13-13 Anti-Aircraft Battery, sir!

50
00:04:41,720 --> 00:04:43,676
All right.

51
00:04:43,760 --> 00:04:46,320
Sergeant Major Bloomer, sir.
"Tiger" to the troops.

52
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:47,958
I can do that!

53
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:54,792
- Sergeant Major Bloomer, do you think?
- Sir?

54
00:04:54,880 --> 00:04:56,438
- Get inside.
- Me, sir?

55
00:04:56,520 --> 00:04:59,751
- Yes, <i>you,</i> sir! Get inside at the double!
- Hargh!

56
00:05:09,920 --> 00:05:11,273
Drop your trousers!

57
00:05:11,360 --> 00:05:14,432
But, sir, we has only just met.

58
00:05:14,520 --> 00:05:17,512
Drop 'em! That's an order!

59
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:18,794
Hah!

60
00:05:33,520 --> 00:05:35,670
- I see.
- Do you, sir?

61
00:05:36,720 --> 00:05:39,837
Sergeant Major, may I ask you a question?

62
00:05:39,920 --> 00:05:43,037
Sir, may I pull up my trousers?

63
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:45,509
What? Oh, yes. Yes. Get 'em up.

64
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:47,556
What I want to know is...

65
00:05:47,640 --> 00:05:51,838
what men in this unit would wear
the kind of underwear I've seen on the line?

66
00:05:51,920 --> 00:05:53,717
Good Lord!

67
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:55,756
Some of them are wearing skirts too!

68
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:58,956
They is not men, sir.

69
00:05:59,040 --> 00:06:00,996
Well, what the blazes are they?

70
00:06:02,560 --> 00:06:04,516
Women, sir.

71
00:06:05,680 --> 00:06:07,636
You mean, <i>female?</i>

72
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:10,757
Yes, sir. Was sir not told, sir?

73
00:06:10,840 --> 00:06:13,991
This is one of these new mixed batteries.

74
00:06:14,080 --> 00:06:18,756
So, that's what the brigadier meant when
he said that this battery was an experiment.

75
00:06:18,840 --> 00:06:21,718
Experiment, sir?
They does not need to experiment.

76
00:06:21,800 --> 00:06:24,712
They gets at it right away and all the time.

77
00:06:25,240 --> 00:06:26,958
(Chattering)

78
00:06:29,760 --> 00:06:31,716
All right, then. Section, halt.

79
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:35,150
Oh, come on! Come on. Put each other down.

80
00:06:35,240 --> 00:06:37,117
(Moaning)

81
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:39,156
Hang about! Hang about!

82
00:06:39,240 --> 00:06:42,471
We don't want to give our new CO
the right idea, do we?

83
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:43,709
(Laughter)

84
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:44,915
Right, right turn.

85
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:49,870
- What's next?
- Right dress, Leonard.

86
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:51,837
Oh, yeah. Er... right dress.

87
00:07:06,240 --> 00:07:09,232
Two inches shorter
and he could see right up my skirt!

88
00:07:14,560 --> 00:07:17,199
- What's your name, Sergeant?
- Willing, sir.

89
00:07:17,280 --> 00:07:19,236
- And yours?
- Able, sir.

90
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:21,993
Well, Willing and Able, will you kindly tell me

91
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:26,119
why it is necessary for you all
to be squashed up like sardines in a tin?

92
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:28,270
It's just our way of keeping warm, sir.

93
00:07:28,360 --> 00:07:30,316
On the hottest day of the year?

94
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:32,470
We've known it hotter than this, sir.

95
00:07:34,880 --> 00:07:37,997
Dress properly! What do you think this is?
A love parade?

96
00:07:38,080 --> 00:07:41,038
Hee-hee-hee! Very witty, sir.

97
00:07:41,120 --> 00:07:43,793
You speak when you're spoken to.
Do you hear me?

98
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:46,758
Adjust your dress!

99
00:07:47,760 --> 00:07:51,036
No, no, no! One arm's length apart.

100
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:54,317
- Did you demonstrate this, Sergeant Major?
- Frequently, sir!

101
00:07:54,400 --> 00:07:56,356
- Then do it again on me.
- Hah!

102
00:07:57,560 --> 00:07:59,516
Parade. Doing as I do!

103
00:07:59,600 --> 00:08:01,909
Right dress!

104
00:08:03,840 --> 00:08:07,594
As you were. Watch me. Watch me!
Right dress!

105
00:08:08,960 --> 00:08:11,190
Doing as I do! As you were! As you were!

106
00:08:11,280 --> 00:08:14,317
Did you not you see what I was doing?
Right dress! As you were!

107
00:08:14,400 --> 00:08:17,836
Not as they were.
Leave them as they are, Sergeant Major.

108
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:20,229
But, sir, as they are is horrible, sir!

109
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:23,153
You're ruining my shoulder, Sergeant.

110
00:08:23,240 --> 00:08:25,196
Sorry, sir.

111
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:27,236
It comes of gripping balls, sir.

112
00:08:27,320 --> 00:08:29,675
- Eh?
- Always has one of these to hand, sir.

113
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:34,470
- Fingers of steel, sir. Fingers of steel.
- Put it away. Let's get on with the inspection.

114
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:44,474
You up there, what's your name?

115
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:46,516
Oh, erm... Ready, sir.

116
00:08:46,600 --> 00:08:48,352
Ready.

117
00:08:48,440 --> 00:08:50,829
Ready, Willing and Able.

118
00:08:50,920 --> 00:08:53,275
- This is ridiculous!
- (Mumbles)

119
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:56,788
- What <i>are</i> you doing?
- Twitching, sir!

120
00:08:56,880 --> 00:09:00,156
I can see that, Sergeant Major,
but <i>why</i> is he twitching?

121
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:02,196
(Mumbles)

122
00:09:03,240 --> 00:09:05,276
It's my woor-uhhhhh...

123
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:07,828
Woorghhhh! It's my nerves, sir.

124
00:09:07,920 --> 00:09:09,876
Trying to twitch your ticket, eh?

125
00:09:09,960 --> 00:09:13,635
Well, it won't work, Bombardier.
You're in the Army for the duration.

126
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:15,676
Twitch your way out of that!

127
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:17,478
Oohhh... eerrrggh!

128
00:09:17,560 --> 00:09:19,755
- Ready!
- (Screams)

129
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:21,796
Twitch off!

130
00:09:21,880 --> 00:09:23,791
It's wasted on me, boy.

131
00:09:23,880 --> 00:09:25,836
Good Lord!

132
00:09:26,880 --> 00:09:28,836
Good heavens!

133
00:09:28,920 --> 00:09:31,388
Good man. And what's your name?

134
00:09:31,480 --> 00:09:34,358
Shorthouse. Gunner Shorthouse, sir.
It's my name.

135
00:09:37,240 --> 00:09:39,196
And what is your name, my man?

136
00:09:39,280 --> 00:09:41,236
Er... woman?

137
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:45,199
Jennifer Ffoukes Sharpe, sir.
The Sharpe with an E and two Fs in the Ffoukes.

138
00:09:45,280 --> 00:09:46,474
How do you do?

139
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:48,278
(Fingers crunch)

140
00:09:48,360 --> 00:09:50,590
She too is a ball squeezer, sir.

141
00:09:52,840 --> 00:09:56,116
Do your shoelace up
and look sharp about it, Sharpe!

142
00:09:59,320 --> 00:10:00,275
(Snarls)

143
00:10:00,360 --> 00:10:02,828
- Ooooh!
- Oh, Tiger!

144
00:10:02,920 --> 00:10:04,876
I think you're wonderful.

145
00:10:04,960 --> 00:10:07,633
When are you going to savage me?

146
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:10,075
If only you was a man, I would sort you out!

147
00:10:11,520 --> 00:10:14,876
Well... you seem to have put your foot in it.

148
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:18,157
Not so much my foot, sir. More my big toe.

149
00:10:18,240 --> 00:10:19,673
What's wrong with it?

150
00:10:19,760 --> 00:10:23,196
Sprained it, sir, didn't I?
When I... erm... fell out of bed.

151
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:26,113
- Pushed out of bed more like!
- Pushed out?

152
00:10:26,200 --> 00:10:28,634
- (Both giggle)
- What are you laughing at?

153
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:32,274
Well, I'm happy, sir.

154
00:10:32,360 --> 00:10:35,113
Happy? What, here?

155
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:38,351
He might have sprained something else,
mightn't he?

156
00:10:41,080 --> 00:10:43,640
- Are you trying to be funny, Gunner?
- Me, sir?

157
00:10:43,720 --> 00:10:45,995
You, sir. Why are you blinking like that?

158
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:48,753
- I'm not blinking, sir. You are.
- I never blink.

159
00:10:48,840 --> 00:10:51,195
- Neither do I, sir.
- You blinking well do!

160
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:54,955
Sergeant Major, which one of us two
is blinking here?

161
00:10:55,040 --> 00:10:58,874
There is only one blinking man blinking here,
Gunner, and that's bloody <i>you!</i>

162
00:10:58,960 --> 00:11:00,518
Thank you, Sergeant Major.

163
00:11:00,600 --> 00:11:04,479
And if I catch you again on parade
wearing my moustache... that moustache,

164
00:11:04,560 --> 00:11:07,074
you'll be on charge for impersonating an officer.

165
00:11:08,120 --> 00:11:09,109
Ooooh!

166
00:11:09,200 --> 00:11:10,997
Later, sir. Later.

167
00:11:12,040 --> 00:11:13,075
Who are you?

168
00:11:13,160 --> 00:11:17,358
- Easy, sir.
- Quite possibly. What's your name?

169
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:19,635
That is it, sir. Alice Easy.

170
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:21,119
Oh.

171
00:11:21,200 --> 00:11:23,760
Well, do your top button up.

172
00:11:23,840 --> 00:11:25,796
I can't. They won't let me.

173
00:11:25,880 --> 00:11:28,474
- Who? Who won't let you?
- Them.

174
00:11:29,520 --> 00:11:31,988
Oh, nonsense. Do 'em up... erm... it up.

175
00:11:35,720 --> 00:11:38,632
Good gracious me!
Stand to attention, you're on parade!

176
00:11:38,720 --> 00:11:40,312
Put those shoulders back!

177
00:11:41,400 --> 00:11:44,198
Oh, I do hope you're regular, sir.

178
00:11:44,280 --> 00:11:46,236
Regular?

179
00:11:46,320 --> 00:11:48,959
- I've been regular for 18 years.
- Oh, good.

180
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:52,271
- That means I can have it back tomorrow.
- (Swallows hard)

181
00:11:52,360 --> 00:11:54,954
- You'll have it back when I'm ready.
- That's all right.

182
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:57,190
No need to strain yourself.

183
00:12:06,680 --> 00:12:09,240
You are a shower!

184
00:12:10,280 --> 00:12:12,714
A shambling shower!

185
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:16,031
And I mean to shake you up
more than somewhat!

186
00:12:16,120 --> 00:12:18,076
- Sergeant Major?
- Hah!

187
00:12:18,160 --> 00:12:21,914
Dismiss this shambling shower from my sight.

188
00:12:22,000 --> 00:12:23,149
Hah!

189
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:30,595
Parade! Right turn!

190
00:12:30,680 --> 00:12:32,636
As you were! As you were!

191
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:34,631
You stupid f...

192
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:39,077
<i>How is I expected to use the proper words</i>
<i>with women present?</i>

193
00:12:39,160 --> 00:12:41,116
Never mind. Never mind.

194
00:12:41,200 --> 00:12:43,236
Just f...

195
00:12:43,320 --> 00:12:44,594
Forget it.

196
00:12:46,480 --> 00:12:48,311
Go away.

197
00:12:56,080 --> 00:12:58,036
(Stomach gurgles)

198
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:00,839
Ah, yes, sir. They gives me a headache too.

199
00:13:00,920 --> 00:13:04,071
It's not a headache. It's the stomach.
There's a button in it.

200
00:13:04,160 --> 00:13:07,436
What you might now call a belly button, sir.
Hee-hee hee-hee!

201
00:13:07,520 --> 00:13:09,476
Oh, shut up!

202
00:13:09,560 --> 00:13:13,109
20 year I've been a sergeant major
and nobody told me to shut up before.

203
00:13:13,200 --> 00:13:15,430
I is the person what tells people to shut up, sir...

204
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:17,351
- Shut up!
- Hah!

205
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:22,436
Now, Sergeant Major,

206
00:13:22,520 --> 00:13:27,275
what, in your opinion, is the thing most
calculated to make things hot for this shower?

207
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:31,752
Well?

208
00:13:32,800 --> 00:13:36,315
What's the matter with you, man?
Have you been struck dumb?

209
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:38,152
- I asked you a question.
- Sir.

210
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:41,755
- Have I got permission to break the silence?
- Of course you have.

211
00:13:41,840 --> 00:13:44,479
Very well, sir. Kindly repeat the question.

212
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:52,112
I repeat, what in your opinion, is the thing most
calculated to make things hot for this shower?

213
00:13:52,200 --> 00:13:54,350
- Only one thing in my book, sir.
- Yes. Yes.

214
00:13:54,440 --> 00:13:57,079
- Firing squad.
- Ah, yes. That's it.

215
00:13:58,960 --> 00:14:01,474
What sort of a suggestion is that,
Sergeant Major?

216
00:14:01,560 --> 00:14:04,199
The only one I has to offer.
I has tried everything else.

217
00:14:04,280 --> 00:14:08,751
Well, thank you. That's been a great help.
I shall have to think for both of us.

218
00:14:10,240 --> 00:14:12,196
I've got it.

219
00:14:12,280 --> 00:14:15,829
- We're going to have an air raid.
- My God, sir! They <i>will</i> panic.

220
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:18,115
- This is just a practice.
- They'll still panic.

221
00:14:18,200 --> 00:14:20,156
Yes, they will, won't they?

222
00:14:20,240 --> 00:14:22,196
- The wind.
- Not me, sir.

223
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:27,070
No, Sergeant Major. The wind is what you
and me are going to put up them.

224
00:14:27,160 --> 00:14:28,878
(Burps)

225
00:14:28,960 --> 00:14:31,633
- Gives me the wind just to look at it.
- Leonard...

226
00:14:31,720 --> 00:14:33,438
- What?
- I've got this feeling.

227
00:14:33,520 --> 00:14:35,829
There's a time and a place for everything.

228
00:14:35,920 --> 00:14:39,151
- Not <i>that</i> kind of feeling.
- I didn't know you had any other.

229
00:14:39,240 --> 00:14:41,356
No! Listen!

230
00:14:41,440 --> 00:14:44,830
I've got this feeling that that new bloke's
going to make trouble for us.

231
00:14:44,920 --> 00:14:47,673
That pipsqueaker?
He's too little to be awkward.

232
00:14:47,760 --> 00:14:51,116
Squash him into the ground.
Not worried about him.

233
00:14:51,200 --> 00:14:53,156
I'm more worried about this.

234
00:14:53,240 --> 00:14:57,438
- Do we eat it or rub it in?
- You can bounce it off the ceiling for all I care.

235
00:14:59,520 --> 00:15:02,956
Right, Sergeant Major.
They should be starting on their pudding.

236
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:05,911
Now! Now, Sergeant Major!

237
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:07,752
- Sir?
- I said now.

238
00:15:07,840 --> 00:15:09,796
- There is no need to shout, sir.
- What?

239
00:15:09,880 --> 00:15:12,872
- There's no need to shout!
- What are you mumbling about?

240
00:15:12,960 --> 00:15:14,996
- There's no need to shout!
- Who is?

241
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:16,593
- I said now!
